  "text": "In practice, the aspect ratio Γ x is too low for convective instability to amplify tiny disturbances that are naturally present in the flow sufficiently so they could be observed before they collide with one of the walls and disappear. For instance, in the study of [CITATION_1] 12 < Γ x < 40, while in most other experimental and numerical studies Γ x ≤ 20. As a result, convective instability would not be observed (and will not be considered in detail here). Instead an absolute instability, a stationary instability, or a combination of both instabilities would occur, and the order in which these instabilities occur would determine the type of convection pattern. In particular, hydrothermal waves (HTW) are usually found for Bo D → 0 and a stationary pattern is found for Bo D = O(1). However, we are not aware of any studies that predict what the pattern might look like at the intermediate values of Bo D . The analysis for large, but finite Γ x (so there are end walls) is presented below.",
